verdict.evidence:
The claim has two separable parts:

PART 1 — "Whether CAMetalDisplayLink officially requires Apple Silicon": REFUTED by the authoritative SDK header. The macOS SDK header at `/Applications/Xcode.app/Contents/Developer/Platforms/MacOSX.platform/Developer/SDKs/MacOSX.sdk/System/Library/Frameworks/QuartzCore.framework/Versions/A/Headers/CAMetalDisplayLink.h` (lines 19, 27, 32) reads:

  API_AVAILABLE(macos(14.0), ios(17.0), tvos(17.0)) API_UNAVAILABLE(watchos)

There is NO Apple Silicon restriction anywhere in the header. The availability condition is purely OS-version-based: macOS 14.0, iOS 17.0, tvOS 17.0. There is no `__arm64__` guard, no `API_AVAILABLE(macos(14.0, arm64))`, no hardware constraint of any kind. The identical header appears verbatim in the iPhoneOS SDK. Apple officially supports CAMetalDisplayLink on any Mac running macOS 14+, Intel or Apple Silicon.

PART 2 — "Moonlight's code gates it with isAppleSilicon() check AND @available(macOS 14, *)": CONFIRMED as an accurate description of Moonlight-Qt's runtime behavior, but this is Moonlight's own defensive choice, NOT an Apple API restriction. The `startDisplayLink()` function in `moonlight-stream/moonlight-qt` at `app/streaming/video/ffmpeg-renderers/vt_metal.mm:812-813` reads:

  if (@available(macOS 14, *)) {
      if (m_MetalDisplayLink != nullptr || !m_MetalLayer.displaySyncEnabled || !isAppleSilicon()) {
          return;
      }

The `isAppleSilicon()` helper (defined in `vt_base.mm:33-47`) uses `sysctlbyname("hw.cputype")` to check for `CPU_TYPE_ARM` at runtime — it has nothing to do with Apple's API declaration. Moonlight added this guard for its own reasons (possibly because CAMetalDisplayLink's ProMotion / frame-pacing benefits are only meaningful on Apple Silicon's ProMotion displays, or to work around observed issues on Intel Macs), not because Apple restricts the API.

SUMMARY: The claim conflates two distinct things. Apple's official API is gated only on macOS 14 (and iOS 17 / tvOS 17) — not on Apple Silicon. Moonlight *additionally* applies an `isAppleSilicon()` runtime guard in its own code for application-level reasons. The original claim's framing that CAMetalDisplayLink is "restricted to Apple Silicon only" is incorrect; the restriction belongs to Moonlight's implementation choice, not to the API.
